 What is Event Propagation?

When an event occurs on an element, it does not only trigger on that element. Instead, it propagates through the DOM tree.

There are 3 phases:

Capturing Phase (Event Capture)

The event starts at the root of the DOM and moves down toward the target element.

Rarely used but can be enabled.

Target Phase

The event reaches the target element where the action happened.

Bubbling Phase (Event Bubble)

The event moves up from the target element to the root (document), triggering handlers along the way.

Most common phase used in JavaScript.

 How to Observe Event Propagation
<div id="outer" style="padding:30px; background:lightblue;">
  Outer Div
  <div id="inner" style="padding:30px; background:lightgreen;">
    Inner Div
    <button id="btn">Click Me</button>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
const outer = document.getElementById("outer");
const inner = document.getElementById("inner");
const btn = document.getElementById("btn");

// Bubbling phase (default)
outer.addEventListener("click", () => console.log("Outer clicked"));
inner.addEventListener("click", () => console.log("Inner clicked"));
btn.addEventListener("click", () => console.log("Button clicked"));
</script>


If you click the button, console output:

Button clicked
Inner clicked
Outer clicked


 This shows bubbling: event goes from target → parent → ancestor.

 Using Capturing Phase

You can capture events on the way down by passing true as the third argument in addEventListener.

outer.addEventListener("click", () => console.log("Outer capturing"), true);
inner.addEventListener("click", () => console.log("Inner capturing"), true);
btn.addEventListener("click", () => console.log("Button capturing"), true);


Clicking button output:

Outer capturing
Inner capturing
Button capturing
Button clicked
Inner clicked
Outer clicked


Capturing first → Target → Bubbling

 Stopping Propagation

Sometimes you don’t want the event to bubble up.

btn.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
  console.log("Button clicked");
  e.stopPropagation(); // stops bubbling
});


Now, only "Button clicked" will log. Inner and Outer won’t get triggered.

 Summary
Concept	Description
Capturing Phase	Event travels top → bottom
Target Phase	Event reaches the target element
Bubbling Phase	Event travels bottom → top (most used)
stopPropagation()	Stops event from going further
preventDefault()	Stops default browser behavior (like form submit)

Event propagation is important for:

Event delegation (handle multiple child elements via parent)

Preventing unwanted actions (stopPropagation)

Controlling UI interactions efficiently